<title>中國古小說與佛教因果觀念=Chinese Ancient Novel and Buddhist Creed of &quot;Wherefore And Therefore&quot;</title>
<author>項裕榮 (著)=Xiang, Yu-rong (au.); 朱蘇權 (著)=Zhu, Su-quan (au.)</author>
<time_orig_str>2006</time_orig_str>
<geo_level1>廣州, 中國 [Guangzhou, China]</geo_level1>
<doctype>期刊論文=Journal Article</doctype>
<compilation_name>廣東技術師範學院學報=Journal of Guangdong Polytechnic Normal University</compilation_name>
<compilation_vol>n.3</compilation_vol>
<xml_metadata>
<Udef_compilation_page>59 - 63</Udef_compilation_page>
<Udef_publisher>
<a target="_blank" href="-">廣東技術師範學院</a>
</Udef_publisher>
<Udef_source>-</Udef_source>
</xml_metadata>
<doc_content>
<Paragraph>中國古小說中以志怪一類對後代影響最巨。此種小說受到佛教因果觀念的影響非常明顯。一方面佛教因果使得古小說的結構上呈現出“因果分明”的完整性；另一方面，報恩、冥報、殺生、輪迴等四種內容的作品也與佛教因果觀關係密切。這些小說的成熟與發展水準，在內容與形式都為此後中國小說的發展提供了借鑑。
Of Chinese Ancient novels it is the ZhiGuai Novels that exerts the most substantial influence upon subsequent novels. The Buddhist influence of its doctrine of &quot;wherefore and therefore&quot; upon this kind of novel shows itself so evidently. On one hand there is some structural integrity of &quot;wherefore and therefore&quot; in this kind of novel; on the other hand, there is some affinity between the creed of &quot;wherefore and therefore&quot; and such outputs as &quot;rewarding&quot;, &quot;Revenge after Death&quot;, &quot;Killing living beings&quot;, &quot;Samsara&quot;. The ripening and development of these kinds of novels offer examples for Chinese novels of later days both in subject and form.</Paragraph>
